

<section>
  <title>Integrals of Trigonometric Functions</title>
  <p>
    When integrating trigonometric functions you will often use a combination of substitution, integration by parts, and trigonometric identities. <xref ref="apptrig">Appendix</xref> has the trigonometric identities that will be necessary for this section: the Pythagorean, double angle, half angle, and product identities.
  </p>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\dsp \int \cos^3(x) \; dx</m> by using the fact that <m>\cos^{3} = \cos^2 \cdot \cos</m> and the Pythagorean identity for <m>\cos^2.</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\dsp \int \cos^5 (x) \; dx</m> by using the fact that <m>\cos^5= \cos^4 \cdot
        \cos</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\dsp \int \cos^{2n+1} (x) \; dx</m> and <m>\dsp \int \sin^{2n+1} (x) \; dx</m> where <m>n</m> is a positive integer.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\dsp \int \sin^4 (x) \; dx</m> using the half-angle identity for <m>\sin.</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate each of the following integrals.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dsp \int \sin^3 (x) \cos^2(x) \; dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dsp \int \sin^3 (x) \cos^5 (x) \; dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dsp \int \sin^4(x) \cos^2 (x) \; dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dsp \int \sin(3x) \cos(6x) \; dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\dsp{ \int \csc(x) \; dx }</m> by first multiplying by <m>\dsp{ \frac{\csc(x) - \cot(x)} {\csc(x) - \cot(x)} }.</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\dsp \int \tan^3(x) \sec^4(x) \; dx</m> in the two different ways indicated.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use <m>\tan^3 \cdot \sec^4 = \tan^2 \cdot \sec^3 \cdot \tan \cdot \sec</m> and the Pythagorean identity for <m>\tan^2.</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Use <m>\tan^3 \cdot \sec^4 = \tan^3 \cdot \sec^2 \cdot \sec^2</m> and the Pythagorean identity for <m>\sec^2.</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate each of the following integrals.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dsp \int \cot^5(x) \; dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dsp \int_{\frac{3\pi}{4}}^{\frac{5\pi}{4}} \sec^4(x) \; dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dsp \int \cot^3(x) \csc^5(x) \; dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dsp \int \tan^2(x) \sec^4(x) \; dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dsp \int \tan^4(x) \sec^3(x) \; dx</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <em>Not for presentation.</em> Integrate the first, second, third, and fourth power of each of the six trigonometric functions. It is a well-documented fact that one of these (24) problems has appeared on at least one test in every Calculus II course since the days of Newton and Leibnitz.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>
</section>

